consciousness_description:
1/ At the beginning, I was slightly more attentive (than usual) to the fact that my window was open and I was wondering what people might think if they saw the flickering light from my screen. However, I was also a lot more attentive to the need to blink, as in it was no longer a reflex, but a conscious action.
(It is possible that I was sleepy because it was late at night when I did the test.)
3/ My state of consciousness was altered in such a way that I thought I was dreaming, or I was about to dream what I was seeing on screen. I also formulated in my head the wish or "prediction" that I was going to dream what I was seeing on screen "later".
4/ I lost track of time, presumably when I was in a dreamlike state. When I "woke up", I looked at the time on the white noise audio reader and I was 8 minutes in. I estimate that I lost a little more than 3 minutes.

consciousness_description:
I tend to forget anything outside of my immediate vision exists (adhd) and the flashing had me forgetting I even had eyes, they kept on unfocusing. I feel nice-ish now (it's slipping as i'm typing this lol) but during it I felt mild dissociation & a bit of concern. I was feeling emptier & less like a person, more like a part of the environment watching itself. This already happens pretty often though. 

When i tried to visualize my friend after staring for 10 mins i still didn't get detail but the image was MUCH more stable. Mental imagery for me feels like straining to see something at the bottom of a pond. For a bit, the brain-water wasn't rippling (it's usually the kind you get with wind? changes & fragments super fast) I could focus on the same thing and felt kinda serene while doing it.

consciousness_change: Lost a sense of time, Alert but hyper-focused on the Ganzflicker, tuning out other external stimuli.
consciousness_description: I immediately noticed my eyes widen and blinking cease.  I am able to cease blinking for several minutes at a time at will (with 30 seconds or so of focus), but in this case I did not intend to go into this state.  It was interesting being almost instantly in that mode, and took focus to break it -- I had to choose to blink rather than choose to not blink.  I also felt like my perception of time was skewing.  I have, ever since I was a young child, had periods where my the flow of time changes to glacial in relation to my mental state.  This includes my movement and bodily responses, with the effect that I'm trapped in my own body.  It is deeply unpleasant.  My experience with the change of sense of time while viewing the Ganzflicker was not the same as these personal episodes (much like how the visual effects I experienced were similar to my migraine auras but lacked the other negative sensations.)  However, because of the similarity I chose to end the visualization.  Within a few seconds of stopping the Ganzflicker, I was fully alert in the here and now.

The kind of rotation would vary. Sometimes, would rotate up and down, other times left to right. For about 10 seconds, though, i saw the shape rotate into itself(?) Like the shape was still itself, but the sides would go into itself while maintaining its shape. Im not sure if that made sense.
emerge_time: A few seconds, It took about half a minute for images to show up, but they were slightly indescribable. The closest thing would probably be some sort of lines starting to carve on the screen. These lines would look like... im not sure if it is possible for whoever is reading this to search for, but if you go online and look up images of an egg, with a bird inside, on a flashlight. And you see like those lines on the egg? Thats what i started to see. Then it took about 40ish seconds for it to change patterns or for other images to show up.
hallucination_frequency: Frequently, Constantly, There were many different images, some vague and some extremely vivid. It would alternate on what felt like 40 seconds, but it was probably mostly irregular. I saw some sort of face sometimes, others would be shapes or rotating shapes. Other times would be landscapes like waterfalls or rainforests (i assume happened because the white noice started to sound like water to me at some point). I also started to see shapes in the form of buildings with oddly shaped windows, but it was more vague than the ither images.
hallucination_intensity: Clear, but not vivid, Clear, vivid, and/or bright, Very vivid, almost real, or popping out of the screen, A majority of what i saw was vivid with the exception of the building. The building was clear to me, but not vivid. It wasn't as present(?) to me as the other images.
hallucination_duration: Persisting several seconds, Constant, morphing from one image to the next, I said before that it felt what could be around 40 seconds for it to change, but i saw over a dozen images so it was probably irregular
consciousness_change: As if in a dreamlike state, Felt transported to another place, Lost a sense of time, Lost a sense of space, I still felt the clothes on me and heard background noises for while, but they started to get blocked out until i forgot them. My sense of time was completely gone after a minute or two, i felt like it went on for well over 10min. Then, with the waterfall image, i forgot i was where i was and felt as if i was levitated above the underwater waterfall.
consciousness_description: At first, I was normal. The white noice was meh, and i didnt really care- i started getting bored. Then I started to experience change in what i was seeing, so i got slightly curious, but felt if i tried to look at it directly, it might dissappear. So i didnt focus on the slight changes. Then, as the noise kept going, the images kept changing, and i started to find it harder and harder to stay concentrated. It was around then that i started to lose my sense of time. Have you ever felt like a second was longer than 5, or a minute shorter than 30seconds? Thats how i felt. Then it got to the waterfall image, and i fully lost myself of that one. It was as if i didnt have any other thought on my mind, except for the sight of that waterfall. And when i heard the drops of water, the sound of the impact felt several seconds long but like an instant at the same time. There were 2~4 drops of water. Then i started to come back to my senses and felt my eyes slightly sore. Then it got to the face and i felt like the noice was drowned out slightly. Then it got to the forest, and i had regained my sense of time fully. Then i stopped at the buildings because my head started to feel irritated, as if i was starting to get a headache. And not to mention that my eyes were sore, as if i didnt blink for a while.
hallucination_location: In the center, In the periphery, All over the screen, It depended on what i saw. The landscapes would be at the center, but the shapes would be on one side of the screen or the other. Sometimes at the top or bottom. Then the lines would be scattered at the edges. I only saw one face but it was pretty wide and it went from the center to the left of my screen (i held my phone sideways)

The Genzlicker Experience felt a lot like meditation. The constant morphing of patterns and images gave me the sensation that I am more than myself, while simultaneously being less. I felt like the part of my brain that understands the interconnectedness of all things became more dominant. The area where my "third eye" is supposed to be became heavy.

It's also nice to know I'm not alone in seeing crazy shit.

consciousness_description:
Earlier I mentioned a bad trip on marijuana. I remember panicking thinking it would last forever. When I'm sober, it's rare but not unusual for me to think about the concept of afterlife, in the sense that if it was "enjoyable" and eternal, would it ever stop being "enjoyable" because of the length of exposure. It makes no sense to me to be "forever in bliss" because I don't believe you can have bliss without downtime. It would become your new normal. 

This experience was more relaxed. I didn't feel too bothered by the illusions. It never occurred to me that I could be trapped and I would hate this existence if it lasted forever. For a few moments, it was more like "if this was the only thing on my mind, I would never notice what I was missing out on". Perhaps "ignorance is bliss" is a bit more literal and spiritual than I thought?

hallucination_categorical: Simple shapes or patterns (e.g., ball of light, lines, grids, spiderwebs, geometric shapes), Colors other than red and black
emerge_time: 5-7 minutes, For the first five or so minutes nothing happened. After that if I focused on any given point for more than a minute it would start to seem to flicker "from" that point (eminating outward). Moreover, I saw "lines" of what looked like indendation in the red (different hue) coming from that point. Also whenver I was focusing on the screen I would begin to see hues of blue inbetween the red, and at one point it appeared yellow.
hallucination_frequency: If I focused on a point for more than a minute I would get it to flicker from there. I had maybe 3 times total where the "lines" appeared. The blue hues were constant after around the 5 minute mark -- In the flashes where red was not visible the screen would be a dark grey blue color. The yellow was only once after maybe 3 minutes of constant focus.
hallucination_intensity: No images, only the screen appearing to be blue.
hallucination_duration: As long as I focused on the screen I could keep the blue hues constant. The yellow hue vanished when I blinked. The lines would remain for a few seconds before essentially being the same as the rest.
consciousness_change: Became relaxed or sleepy, Slight to Moderate sense of dread.
consciousness_description: When I would stare at a point on screen for a while my focus would sort of fade, like what usually happens when you try to focus on the same thing for a while - your mind wants to wander - Those moments of losing focus were somewhat relaxing, but I remained mostly alert. The whole experience made me feel vaguely uneasy, like a sense of dread in the back of my mind, although it was not severe.

consciousness_description: I am going to go out on a limb here and say that I think this Ganzflicker is producing a Beta wave state in my brain.  I'd even say it is in the high end of the Beta range, close to a Gamma wave.  As soon as the flickering light began my first change in consciousness was missing my old CRT monitor.  The LCD can't strobe the entire screen as evenly and intensely as those old tube monitors.  But I decided to make the most of what I have got, so I lightly closed my eyes and leaned back a little in my chair.  I intentionally relaxed and turned off the usual flow of words in my mind.  Entering a meditative state and breathing deeply, I began to see hallucinatory patterns right away.  They shifted to a pattern, a character, a scene, and back to flickering light.  I thought, "this is fun! I wonder how long I have been using it?" So I opened my eyes to check the time.  Looked like about 2 minutes.  Easy to shift out of the Ganzflicker hallucinations and back to full waking consciousness.  How long until I need to get ready for work?  Time noted, I went back into the Ganzflicker.  Felt relaxed but mentally aroused by the experience.  Overall it was nice, but I was eventually longing for greater user-control.  I would enjoy very much the ability to adjust the speed and color of the flashing.  Best if these adjustments are in very fine increments, and the hotkeys for this are live during the experience.  I believe this would allow the user to fine-tune the Ganzflicker for maximum effect.  I'd suggest using directional arrows (up = faster, left = color shift toward red) - that way the user can rest one hand on these familiar arrows and steer the experience without much mental overhead. Thanks for sharing your research with me.  Have a nice day.

consciousness_description: I don't have language to describe it, but I will try. I was still me. I moved around the hallucinations as if I  were a free agent and could look around at will, too, as things caught my attention. The hallucinations were both utterly random also affected by my thoughts. For example, the planet Jupiter emerged from stripes that caught my eye, then began rotation and revolutions and when I thought of the name "Jupiter" it morphed into Roman statuary, then a garden with statues. I could walk and look around before the next change. It was akin to dreaming: random imagery being taken up and given bits of story to make sense of it, then the story influencing the visuals. The sounds were the same, random sounds became echoes of voices and footsteps reverberating against marble and tile and tile as those sounds and thoughts emerged and strengthened their impressions. Then I was in the waiting room of something like the train station with all that visual and auditory type imagery.

consciousness_description: I definitely felt more relaxed through it after a minute or two. When I head the white noise by itself, it sounded loud and uncomfortable, but with the flickering it was peaceful and welcome. Then I lost track of time completely. It went by much faster than I expected, so the  images may have lasted longer than it felt too. And when I had the screen farther from my face and then felt absorbed into the light, it seemed like the space around me became inconsequential and unbound. Like the space I had created between me and the screen no longer existed, I was in the ever changing, flickering world. At the end it felt very dreamlike with how vivid the images became, and I almost wondered if I was falling asleep, but then I'd blink my eyes and they had been fully open. I wanted that feeling to last longer and be even stronger, but I felt much more taken out of it once the white noise stopped. Next time I'll have a longer loop play. And this would be very interesting with marijuana, which the couple times I have taken an edible of it, my visual prowess was enhanced to create extremely powerful and vivid and complex images and thoughts. Multiple at the same time. So I will probably do this again while under the influence in the future.  .

consciousness_change: Became relaxed or sleepy, Felt transported to another place, I "felt transported" in more of an emotional way. At first, the red flashing startled me and I thought I was going to be uncomfortable and almost didn't do the experiment at all. But within seconds I starting seeing things and I was immediately nostalgic for my early childhood, when I would see hallucinations (didn't realize that's what it was then) at night. They weren't scary or complex or anything — it was just a variety of toys and animals and objects I was familiar with at the time floating together across my room or ceiling or whatever. Honestly I think they helped me go to sleep for a long time. So, feeling that way again, I just felt relaxed, entertained, happy, and afterwards, pretty sleepy.

consciousness_description:
My sense of time would constantly vary but was generally quite slow.

Otherwise I would transition from the relaxed and sleepy state to the dreamlike unless if I brought myself to attention. I would then be in a relatively normal state of mind until I allowed myself to lose focus again.

During the former though it was a lot like doing those relaxation exercises where you progress from moving the muscles in your feet and no longer using them, then your lower leg muscles, etc. My focus would vary and the dreamlike state for me was near identical to that of when you daydream and you get lost in your head. A few times I found myself slack-jawed too. I could bring myself to being fully alert during either of these states.

consciousness_change: Felt transported to another place, Lost a sense of time, Lost a sense of space, dread, fear, anxiety that I was being watched
consciousness_description:
I couldn't shake an anxious feeling that I was going to be attacked. As I watched the flicker and listened to the static, it felt almost as though I was straining to see a threatening shape at night, and listen for its movements, but there was so much noise (as opposed to signal) that I couldn't make it out, and that if I didn't manage to I was in danger. I noticed afterwards that I was sweating slightly, and that my eyes were dry from holding them open too wide and too long. 

also, it's hard to explain, but at times I felt like the flickering on the screen was growing out of my computer and not just enveloping my vision, but becoming my vision, with no clear boundary between what I was seeing and what I was looking at. This was strongly coupled with losing my sense of time, and when the static stopped playing I was quite surprised that ten minutes had already gone by.

Incidentally, it is very odd to me to imagine anything approximating a dreamlike or sleepy reaction to the experience. I feel like I need to do something cathartic and relaxing to shake the lingering malaise that thing gave me.

consciousness_description: As I said above, I felt very relaxed but almost hypnotized and when the 10 minutes were up at felt like no time has passed at all. I found myself feeling pretty hyper-focused but not in an uncomfortable way. As I previously mentioned, I found myself wishing I was seeing more so I felt motivated to stay focused but I did my best to not let this pressure my experience. I felt excited and curious to try this and found myself intrigued and able to enjoy flashing screen even though it felt strange at first. I was surprised at how immediately calm I felt when the flashing started.

I don't recall ever noticing a horizon nor any object at apparently great distance.
consciousness_description: I felt mostly curious and interested, as if on a pleasant hike or evening stroll. The quick changes between perceiving geometric patterns (mostly interpreted as tiles, glazed-bricks, et al. antiseptic, indoor environments) and trees or pond-like reflections (almost entirely interpreted as exterior, natural environments) was disorienting, but not unpleasant. I felt in almost constant, but slow paced motion, very much as if walking past scenery, occasionally panning (sweeping my view from side to side), and occasionally stopping to gaze more fixedly and quietly at a given, pleasant scene (e.g. a sky reflected in a pond, or a wave crashing on a beach).

Very relaxed and calm, but still aware of my surroundings. A strange sensation that I guess in a word could best be described as feeling "disconnected" that persists for some time afterwards - for example I am obviously still in full control of my body and can type normally into this box and although I'm composing what I'm writing as normal it feels almost like my hands are doing their own thing, typing on their own.

consciousness_change: Became relaxed or sleepy, Lost a sense of time, Lost a sense of space, Near hypnogogic state.
consciousness_description: The feeling I got, may have been self imposed. Most of my life I have experienced various phenomena, most relevant here are sleep paralysis, hypnogogic hallucinations, and visual snow. My first encounter with sleep paralysis turned me into a skeptic and an amateur brain science nerd. I have reviewed a lot of the research behind this stuff, and I love it, but I have also delved into meditation and experimented with trying to reach altered mental states as well. Some of the fruit of that work, is that I have at least a few times, managed to trigger hypnogogic hallucinations while awake, and standing up. I may have contaminated your results a bit, as I used those techniques here, to test and see if the experience was at all enhanced. (I never use binaural beats for meditative purposes because of the quackery involved with that, however upon reading the theory behind this research, I was reminded of the neurology behind why we hear binaural beats and decided to throw that in the background on a hunch.) While the hallucinations were present, they were actually less vivid than those experiences, where the hallucinations were indistinguishable from reality, except that they were absurd. However like with those experiences, the imagery was random and uncontrollable. Given the patterns I saw today, I would not rule out the potential for them to be interference patterns from the refresh rate of the display, however the patterns appeared to move with my eyes, and not maintain lock to any part of the displays within the headset. Also, what is most interesting to me, is that all of these images, were the imagery I see during migraine but enhanced. The spinning spiral, and the moving patterns, were all very reminiscent of that. Moreso, I have a condition (I would hardly call it that, it's non-debilitating for the most part, except it messes with my eyes while driving at night) called visual snow. There is very little research into this phenomena, but I had found and had a brief correspondence with James T. Fulton, Director of Research, at Neural Concepts in Newport Beach, Ca. who seemed to think, based on his research there, that visual snow is related to edema localized to the anterior horn of the left or right lateral ventricle. The condition manifests for me as a consistent, and rapid shifting grain, that resembles and behaves like fine grain television static over my entire field of vision, regardless of if my eyes are open or closed, that is distinguishable from blue field entopic effect, phosphenes, and migraine phenomena (which appear to be on the same "layer" of my vision, but geometric and non-random like the snow. This is hard to describe). Occasionally the snow will appear to manifest random "imagery" sometimes just shapes, and sometimes just random streaks across my vision, though these are both rare, and in my meditation I had noticed that the vivid imagery seems to come about from changes in this "static field". I lack the scientific resources to study this under any sort of control, so it is impossible for me to really determine how the snow is related, whether the snow is connected to the same parts of the brain that create hallucinations, or if the random patterns in the snow, is seeding hallucinations via pareidolia. I bring it up, because that too seemed to play a part in what I was seeing here, but all enhanced. I would really like to see some of this stuff taken into account with this research as it could lead to some better understandings all around.

consciousness_description: I set two timers for this: one for ten minutes, and another for twenty. I didn't hear either of them (headphones worked better than I thought), and what I thought had been 15 minutes was actually 30. As for dissociation, it would happen every time I stopped concentrating - my vision would get softer and I'd zone out. This didn't surprise me, I expect these sorts of activities to trigger my dissociative disorder. What did surprise me was that I could catch myself dissociating, then stay in the gray zone (aware of my surroundings but my vision still in soft focus) apparently as long as I chose. I tried to stay grounded, though, and I think the most interesting images occurred when I felt I was fully alert.

consciousness_description: My thoughts started to wander a lot at the beginning, but towards the end I was watching it and letting what I saw lead my thoughts.  It was pleasant, like having that feeling of curiosity about something and watching it to see what happens.  Sort of like I had given my mind a blank canvas to project onto, and once my thoughts stopped wandering, it felt like I was just observing the canvas to see what my mind started to create on it.  It felt similar to curiosity also in that I lost track of time.  I only did it for 10 minutes because I set a timer on my watch, and 10 minutes felt like it passed by very quickly.  Like how you lose track of time when you are engrossed in learning or observing something that you are curious about.

consciousness_description: I never could make i past the 7 minute mark. as the video progressed, it made my vision start to blur, my eyes lose focus and almost cross, and I became almost in a trance. My eyes kept drooping down, and finally closing with my head drooped down. But, right before my eyes fully closed, and I was out of focus but looking through the eyelashes right before they shut, THEN I could see the most detail. It was very brief and mostly at the bottom of the screen, but my eyes would shut so I lost it. Then in my eyelids (if that makes sense, it was a large black rectangle with bursts behind it. I tried it twice and was so disappointed!!! I wanted it to work SO BAD. OOH! on a previous page about what i saw, I did have a little light coming from the next room beside me. In front of me, I can see into the dark living room. Okay, both times I watched the video, towards the top right corner OUTSIDE of my laptop over in the distance, I saw movement that I know wasn't really there, and as soon as my eyes left the screen, it was gone. That happened a couple of times each time.

consciousness_description:
I felt as though the flashing light wanted me to watch it (to be very clear: I did *not* feel as though I considered it to have a consciousness of its own), or that I felt entirely compelled to do so.

I was also, at the same time, quite bored, but (through a roughly equal mix of wishing to commit to the experiment, and said feeling of compulsion) felt unable to look away, though I did wish that the time would pass faster.

Purely for reference: when I encounter strobe lighting in a theatre, the best description of my mental response I have been able to come up with is "it feels as though the light is trying to kill me" - again, not to ascribe it an actual mind, merely that I feel as though it has a great deal of menace and has somehow taken control of *my* mind. I am aware this is not entirely regular, though have not yet been to see a doctor for any diagnosis that might actually make this a useful point of reference to you, as it is a rather manageable state of affairs.

consciousness_description: Despite being fully, consciously aware of and connected to my body and immediate surroundings, there was a sense of being... I'm not sure.  Dazed, perhaps?  Disoriented?  And of floating through an abstract space.  It stood out to me during the time that it seemed like I should have more trouble with proprioception given how I was feeling.  I can confirm my proprioception _was_ working properly though:  I was laying on my back with the laptop balanced on my chest, and using my arms to blot out the sides of my field of vision and the macOS menu bar (to reduced light intrusion even more), so I had to make adjustments fairly continuously.   I had a definite sense that once this ended I would be _very_ disoriented for at least a solid minute or more.  That sense proved largely wrong:  Once the experience ended, the sense of disorientation mostly subsided within a few seconds.  I still have a certain background fuzziness I'm feeling right now, like you might have 10 minutes after going on a very intense roller coaster ride.

hallucination_categorical: Colors other than red and black, white jagged lines radiating randomly from an undefined center
hallucination_duration: Overall pattern was constant yet changing in detail .
consciousness_change: I shifted my attention inward to allow the flickering light to wash over me.
consciousness_description: I distanced myself from the changing flickering light and felt a solid unchanging sense of self that was my core being. I could have continued, but, there was a concern as my body temperature rose that it may not be in my best interest to do so. I wondered that if thru a brain event like a stroke I saw this visual for the rest of my life...could I cope.  That solid core of self said maybe. I pondered if I could sufficiently put distance between that unchanging sense of self and the unrelenting stimulation to body and mind. Could that stimulation become background noise before I went crazy?  The experiment is over and I am content to go back to my everyday consciousness knowing that I am not the body and I am not even the mind... I am something more permanent than either.

hallucination_intensity: Clear, but not vivid, halfway through, I saw line drawings of all sorts of things (cars, screwdrivers, faces, mugs, cartoon characters) changing very rapidly
hallucination_duration: Brief moment or flash, Constant, morphing from one image to the next
consciousness_change: Became relaxed or sleepy, Felt transported to another place, Lost a sense of time, Lost a sense of space
consciousness_description: At first, the blinking lights felt uncomfortable, like I was drunk, and the spinning made me slightly nauseous, but that ended quickly; I liked the blinking, which turned into beautiful colored blobs pulsing and floating; the pale grid/spiderweb lines ebbed and flowed, with the color blobs beneath; the multiple spinning wheels/flowers went clockwise, then counterclockwise, and came and went; I felt very calm and meditative, comfortable; I liked the experience bc it reminded me of times I ride the commuter train when the sun sets and we go past a line of trees...I close my eyes and see a similar scene but with much more varied and brilliant colors; I closed my eyes during this ganzflicker experience and saw purple and black soothing, sinuous waves of wet sand; I was relaxed and wanted to nap but roused up to continue watching. (I would do this again just for the fun of it. I wish there were more colors than just black and red. I would love to see all different colors pulsing and blinking!) I feel very calm writing this. thank you.

consciousness_description: I was mostly alert with minimal change. Around perhaps 7 minutes in I felt sleepy for a few moments, which I welcomed as I am doing this immediately prior to starting my evening routine prior to sleep. Sporadically, I felt moments of brief anxiety. While I have a diagnosed anxiety disorder (generalized anxiety disorder, primarily exhibiting as a constant state of moderately increased anxiety when not controlled with medicated), the anxiety spikes were convincingly causally linked to the visual phenomena. The brief spikes are not an uncommon expression of anxiety for me, though they are typically an immediate response to a negative stressor. Aside from these brief spikes and a relatively short period of drowsiness, I was not notably influenced by viewing the Ganzflicker during those 10 minutes.
